# SpecVM Architecture Redesign — Implementation Plan

## Problem Summary

The SpecVM rendering pipeline (`MotionSpec JSON → SpecPlayer → Remotion → Video`) suffers from runtime crashes, missing renderer support, malformed spec tolerance failures, and inability to handle complex animations (charts, staggered text, multi-object coordination). Error traces show 34 documented failures across spec compilation, code generation, and runtime layers.

---

## 1. Current System Analysis

### Architecture Overview

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A["LLM"] --> B["MotionSpec JSON"]
    B --> C["SpecPlayer.tsx"]
    C --> D["computeObjectState()"]
    D --> E["renderObject()"]
    E --> F["Remotion render → Video"]
```

The runtime is 6 files (~850 lines total):

| File | Lines | Role |
|---|---|---|
| [types.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/types.ts) | 162 | TypeScript interfaces for MotionSpec format |
| [animationRuntime.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/animationRuntime.ts) | 293 | Per-frame interpolation engine |
| [rendererRegistry.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/rendererRegistry.ts) | 72 | Shape → renderer function mapping |
| [SpecPlayer.tsx](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/SpecPlayer.tsx) | 53 | Main Remotion component |
| [shapeRenderers.tsx](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/shapeRenderers.tsx) | 160 | circle, square, rectangle, triangle, line renderers |
| [mediaRenderers.tsx](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/mediaRenderers.tsx) | 112 | svg, image, text renderers |

### Key Weaknesses Identified

#### W1: SpecVM doesn't support many properties that specs actually use

The LLM-generated specs (v2) use properties the SpecVM **ignores silently**:

| Property | Used in specs | Supported by SpecVM |
|---|---|---|
| `height` animation | ✅ (all bar charts) | ❌ Not in [animationRuntime.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/animationRuntime.ts) |
| `width` animation | ✅ (bar/line charts) | ❌ Not in [animationRuntime.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/animationRuntime.ts) |
| `anchor` | ✅ (bar positioning) | ❌ Not in [SceneObject](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/types.ts#47-74) type or any renderer |
| `fill` (false = outline only) | ✅ (outlined shapes) | ❌ Not in type or renderers |
| `facing` (triangle direction) | ✅ (triangle variants) | ❌ Not in type or renderers |
| `cornerRadius` | ✅ (rounded rects) | ❌ Not in type or renderers |
| `scaleX` / `scaleY` | ✅ (directional scaling) | ❌ Not in type or runtime |

> [!CAUTION]
> The SpecVM **has** `size` animation support in [animationRuntime.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/animationRuntime.ts) (line 250-254), but the actual spec format uses `height: [0, 60]` and `width: [0, 80]` as separate properties. The runtime only handles `size: [[fromW, fromH], [toW, toH]]` — a compound property. **Every bar chart animation silently does nothing** because the `height` timeline events are ignored.

#### W2: No spec validation — malformed specs crash the renderer

- No type checking at ingestion time
- `NaN` values from malformed tuples propagate to `interpolate()` → Remotion throws
- Missing `objects` or `timeline` arrays cause `TypeError: Cannot read property 'map' of undefined`
- Timeline events targeting nonexistent objects are silently skipped
- No fallback for missing `canvas`, `fps`, or `duration`

#### W3: No error boundaries in SpecPlayer

A single bad object crashes the entire composition. There's no try-catch around [computeObjectState()](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/animationRuntime.ts#147-293) or [renderObject()](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/rendererRegistry.ts#45-72).

#### W4: Text renderer has layout issues

- Text uses `whiteSpace: "nowrap"` but no width constraint → long text overflows
- No text wrapping for multiline content (e.g., legend `"Cloud\nLicensing\nServices"`)
- Text position is not centered on coordinate — only `left: 50%, top: 50%` + translate, but no `margin` offset like shapes have

#### W5: Duplicate [buildTransform](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/shapeRenderers.tsx#14-22) helper

[shapeRenderers.tsx](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/shapeRenderers.tsx) (line 14) and [mediaRenderers.tsx](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/mediaRenderers.tsx) (line 12) have identical [buildTransform](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/shapeRenderers.tsx#14-22) functions. DRY violation.

#### W6: Line renderer produces zero-height elements

In spec_157, gridlines have `size: [1200, 0]`. The line renderer does `Math.max(h, strokeWidth)` which gives `Math.max(0, 2)` = 2, but only if stroke is present. Lines without stroke get `height: 0` → invisible.

#### W7: Console.log left in SpecPlayer

Line 38: `console.log("Rendering spec:", spec.scene);` runs every frame (~30fps × duration).

---

## 2. Architecture Decision

### Evaluation of Suggestions

#### Suggestion A — Scene Graph: ❌ REJECTED (for now)

**Reasoning:**
- The current flat `objects[]` + `timeline[]` model is actually well-suited for the LLM generation use case. LLMs generate flat lists more reliably than nested hierarchies.
- Chart layouts don't need parent-child transform inheritance — they need correct **positioning math** and **anchor-based growth**, which is a rendering concern, not a structural one.
- Adding a scene graph adds complexity that would make specs harder for LLMs to generate correctly.
- The real problem isn't the data structure — it's that the **renderer doesn't support the properties the specs actually use**.

**Future consideration:** A lightweight grouping mechanism (`group` property) could be added in Phase 4 if needed for complex scene orchestration.

#### Suggestion B — Spec Validation Layer: ✅ ACCEPTED

**Reasoning:**
- Error traces show many failures from malformed values, missing properties, and invalid types
- A validation + normalization layer prevents 100% of crash-from-bad-spec failures
- It's cheap to implement and has massive reliability payoff
- It catches LLM mistakes before they hit the renderer

### Proposed Pipeline

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["MotionSpec JSON"] --> B["specValidator.ts\n(validate + warn)"]
    B --> C["specNormalizer.ts\n(defaults + sanitize)"]
    C --> D["SpecPlayer.tsx\n(with error boundaries)"]
    D --> E["computeObjectState()\n(expanded property support)"]
    E --> F["renderObject()\n(expanded renderers)"]
    F --> G["Remotion render → Video"]
    
    B -.->|"validation errors"| H["Structured error log"]
    F -.->|"unknown shape"| I["Fallback placeholder"]
```

---

## 3. Proposed Changes — Multi-Phase

### Phase 1: Stability & Crash Prevention

> **Goal:** No spec should ever crash the renderer. Every spec produces a video (even if visually incomplete).

---

#### [MODIFY] [types.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/types.ts)

Add missing properties to [SceneObject](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/types.ts#47-74) and [TimelineEvent](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/types.ts#79-116) that specs actually use:

```diff
 export interface SceneObject {
   id: string;
   shape: string;
   size?: [number, number];
   diameter?: number;
   color?: string;
   opacity?: number;
   pos?: [number, number];
   shadow?: ShadowDefinition;
   stroke?: StrokeDefinition;
   text?: TextDefinition;
   src?: string;
   scale?: number;
   rotation?: number;
+  anchor?: "center" | "bottom" | "left" | "top" | "right";
+  fill?: boolean;
+  facing?: "up" | "down" | "left" | "right";
+  cornerRadius?: number;
+  zIndex?: number;
 }
```

```diff
 export interface TimelineEvent {
   target: string;
   time: [number, number];
   easing?: string;
   opacity?: [number, number];
   scale?: [number, number];
   rotation?: [number, number];
   x?: [number, number];
   y?: [number, number];
   diameter?: [number, number];
   color?: [string, string];
   pos?: [[number, number], [number, number]];
   size?: [[number, number], [number, number]];
+  width?: [number, number];
+  height?: [number, number];
+  cornerRadius?: [number, number];
+  scaleX?: [number, number];
+  scaleY?: [number, number];
   shadow?: { ... };
   stroke?: { ... };
   text?: { ... };
 }
```

