### Phase 2: Spec Validation & Normalization

> **Goal:** Every spec entering the pipeline is well-formed, with sane defaults and no crash-causing values.

---

#### [NEW] [specValidator.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/specValidator.ts)

Validation functions:
- `validateSpec(spec: unknown): { valid: boolean; errors: string[]; warnings: string[] }`
- Check required fields (`duration`, `fps`, `objects`, `timeline`)
- Check all `time` tuples are `[number, number]` with `start <= end`
- Check all animation tuples are numeric `[from, to]` (not strings, not null)
- Check all `target` references resolve to existing objects
- Check all `color` values are parseable (hex, rgb, rgba)
- Check `objects` have unique `id` values
- Return structured warnings (not crashes) for unknown properties

---

#### [NEW] [specNormalizer.ts](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/specNormalizer.ts)

Normalization functions:
- `normalizeSpec(spec: MotionSpec): MotionSpec`
- Fill missing `canvas` with `{ w: 1920, h: 1080 }`
- Fill missing `fps` with `30`
- Fill missing `bg` with `"#000000"`
- Clamp `opacity` values to `[0, 1]`
- Convert `duration_sec` → `duration` (LLM sometimes uses wrong name)
- Strip `NaN` / `Infinity` from numeric values → replace with `0`
- Remove timeline events targeting nonexistent objects (with warning)
- Coerce single-value animation tuples: `opacity: [1]` → `opacity: [1, 1]`
- Sort timeline events by start time for deterministic order

---

