## 5. Migration Strategy

All changes are **backwards-compatible**. The approach:

1. New optional fields in types → existing specs remain valid
2. Normalization fills defaults → specs without new fields still work
3. New renderers are additive → existing shapes unaffected
4. Error boundaries protect existing working specs from new code bugs
5. No changes to [Root.tsx](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/Root.tsx), [batchRunner.js](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/scripts/batchRunner.js), or spec format required

After implementation, re-run the batch suite to compare:
- Previously passing specs should still pass
- Previously failing specs (spec_137, spec_154, spec_157, spec_166, spec_170) should now render

---

## 6. Future Extensibility

The architecture naturally extends to:

- **SVG objects**: Add `renderSVGShape` to registry, no core changes needed
- **Charts as composite renderers**: Register `"barChart"` shape that internally creates bars + labels + axes
- **Scene graph (if needed later)**: Add optional `parent` field to [SceneObject](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/types.ts#47-74), process hierarchy in [computeObjectState](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/animationRuntime.ts#147-293)
- **Spring animations**: Add `spring` easing in [resolveEasing](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/animationRuntime.ts#20-48) using Remotion's `spring()` API
- **Path animations**: Add `path` property to [TimelineEvent](file:///Users/durgesh/Desktop/shape-motion-lab/src/specvm/types.ts#79-116) for motion along bezier curves

